      <hedline>
        <hl1>Ladies' Table Manners</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lelde Gilman letter disagrees with comments in May 30 article on 'ladylike' table manners</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Who Can Explain 'Ladylike'? Real Ladies, Age 16 to 98'' (Fashion page, May 30):</p>
        <p>I am much amused and also saddened by Brooke Astor's observations in regard to the sage advice of her grandmother, who said that a lady should always leave something on her plate. She follows it with, ''To want to enjoy one's dinner is correct, but greed is not.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Who Can Explain 'Ladylike'? Real Ladies, Age 16 to 98'' (Fashion page, May 30):</p>
        <p>I am much amused and also saddened by Brooke Astor's observations in regard to the sage advice of her grandmother, who said that a lady should always leave something on her plate. She follows it with, ''To want to enjoy one's dinner is correct, but greed is not.''</p>
        <p>Only in overfed yet constantly dieting America is deliberate waste of food construed as greed!</p>
        <p>In European polite society one is taught that respect for food and the cook is best shown by eating what is on the plate while exhibiting superb table manners.</p>
        <p>LELDE GILMAN  Portland, Ore., May 30, 2000</p>
      </block>
